y:Transtheism]]\n", "name_user": "98.116.17.201", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(i just put all the benefits of what they believe)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animism"}
{"title_page": "Dear April", "text_new": "<br />{{Infobox song\n| name       = Dear April\n| cover      = Dear April Frank Ocean.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Frank Ocean]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Dear April\" ([[Justice (band)|Justice]] remix)\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|03|25}}<!-- Only original vinyl release date should be included here; digital release date is mentioned in the article's body-->\n| format     =\n* [[7-inch single|7-inch]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n| genre      =<!-- Sourced in body of article; do not add unsourced genres -->\n* [[Ambient pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:51\n| label      = Blonded\n| writer     =\n* Frank Ocean\n* [[Daniel Aged]]\n| producer   = \n* Frank Ocean\n* Daniel Aged\n| prev_title = [[In My Room (Frank Ocean song)|In My Room]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title2     = [[Cayendo]]\n}}\n\"'''Dear April'''\" is a song by [[Frank Ocean]], released as a [[7-inch single]] on March 25, 2020, consisting of an \"[[acoustic music|acoustic]]\" version as side A, and a remix by [[Justice (band)|Justice]] as side B. The acoustic version was released digitally on April 3, and was written and produced by Ocean and [[Daniel Aged]].\n\n==Background and release==\nIn October 2019, Ocean previewed [[Justice (band)|Justice]]'s remix of the track at his PrEP+ club night, and made the 7-inch single avaiable to pre-order on his website, alongside \"[[Cayendo]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/frank-ocean-previews-new-songs-dear-april-and-cayendo-listen/|title=Frank Ocean Previews New Songs \"Dear April\" and \"Cayendo\": Listen|last1=Sodomsky|first1=Sam|last2=Monroe|first2=Jazz|date=October 19, 2019|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, the vinyls began to ship, while the acoustic A-side was released on digital platforms on April 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/frank-ocean-releases-vinyl-exclusive-singles-dear-april-and-cayendo/|title=Frank Ocean releases vinyl-exclusive singles, 'Dear April' and 'Cayendo'|last=Mao|first=Jessica|date=March 31, 2020|website=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/frank-ocean-releases-new-songs-dear-april-and-cayendo/|title=Frank Ocean Releases New Songs \"Dear April\" and \"Cayendo\": Listen|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=April 3, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nOcean wrote and produced the song with [[Daniel Aged]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/136270534/credits|title=Credits / Dear April (Side A - Acoustic) / Frank Ocean|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> It has been characterised as an [[ambient pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] ballad, featuring a dream-like atmosphere with jazz-influenced guitars and \"synth-like washes\".<ref name=\"PFReview\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/frank-ocean-dear-april/|title=\"Dear April\" by Frank Ocean Review|last=Hogan|first=Marc|date=April 3, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/03/826616962/frank-ocean-drops-new-music-with-singles-dear-april-and-cayendo|title=Frank Ocean Drops New Music With Singles 'Dear April' And 'Cayendo'|last=Lewis|first=Jon|website=[[NPR]]|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nFor ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', Marc Hogan described the song as potentially Ocean's \"most understated stunner yet\", writing: \"It\u2019s not the Ocean you would\u2019ve wanted to see at the now-postponed [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]], but it\u2019s the Ocean we needed to hear holed up alone together in our bedrooms.<ref name=\"PFReview\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 7-inch single\n| title1 = Dear April\n| note1 = acoustic\n| length1 = 3:51\n| title2 = Dear April\n| note2 = [[Justice (band)|Justice]] remix\n| length2 = 4:11\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Frank Ocean songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Frank Ocean]]\n", "text_old": "Category:2020 singles{{Infobox song\n| name       = Dear April\n| cover      = Dear April Frank Ocean.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Frank Ocean]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = \"Dear April\" ([[Justice (band)|Justice]] remix)\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|03|25}}<!-- Only original vinyl release date should be included here; digital release date is mentioned in the article's body-->\n| format     =\n* [[7-inch single|7-inch]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n| genre      =<!-- Sourced in body of article; do not add unsourced genres -->\n* [[Ambient pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:51\n| label      = Blonded\n| writer     =\n* Frank Ocean\n* [[Daniel Aged]]\n| producer   = \n* Frank Ocean\n* Daniel Aged\n| prev_title = [[In My Room (Frank Ocean song)|In My Room]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title2     = [[Cayendo]]\n}}\n\"'''Dear April'''\" is a song by [[Frank Ocean]], released as a [[7-inch single]] on March 25, 2020, consisting of an \"[[acoustic music|acoustic]]\" version as side A, and a remix by [[Justice (band)|Justice]] as side B. The acoustic version was released digitally on April 3, and was written and produced by Ocean and [[Daniel Aged]].\n\n==Background and release==\nIn October 2019, Ocean previewed [[Justice (band)|Justice]]'s remix of the track at his PrEP+ club night, and made the 7-inch single avaiable to pre-order on his website, alongside \"[[Cayendo]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/frank-ocean-previews-new-songs-dear-april-and-cayendo-listen/|title=Frank Ocean Previews New Songs \"Dear April\" and \"Cayendo\": Listen|last1=Sodomsky|first1=Sam|last2=Monroe|first2=Jazz|date=October 19, 2019|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, the vinyls began to ship, while the acoustic A-side was released on digital platforms on April 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/frank-ocean-releases-vinyl-exclusive-singles-dear-april-and-cayendo/|title=Frank Ocean releases vinyl-exclusive singles, 'Dear April' and 'Cayendo'|last=Mao|first=Jessica|date=March 31, 2020|website=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/frank-ocean-releases-new-songs-dear-april-and-cayendo/|title=Frank Ocean Releases New Songs \"Dear April\" and \"Cayendo\": Listen|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=April 3, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nOcean wrote and produced the song with [[Daniel Aged]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/136270534/credits|title=Credits / Dear April (Side A - Acoustic) / Frank Ocean|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> It has been characterised as an [[ambient pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] ballad, featuring a dream-like atmosphere with jazz-influenced guitars and \"synth-like washes\".<ref name=\"PFReview\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/frank-ocean-dear-april/|title=\"Dear April\" by Frank Ocean Review|last=Hogan|first=Marc|date=April 3, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/03/826616962/frank-ocean-drops-new-music-with-singles-dear-april-and-cayendo|title=Frank Ocean Drops New Music With Singles 'Dear April' And 'Cayendo'|last=Lewis|first=Jon|website=[[NPR]]|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nFor ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', Marc Hogan described the song as potentially Ocean's \"most understated stunner yet\", writing: \"It\u2019s not the Ocean you would\u2019ve wanted to see at the now-postponed [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]], but it\u2019s the Ocean we needed to hear holed up alone together in our bedrooms.<ref name=\"PFReview\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 7-inch single\n| title1 = Dear April\n| note1 = acoustic\n| length1 = 3:51\n| title2 = Dear April\n| note2 = [[Justice (band)|Justice]] remix\n| length2 = 4:11\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Frank Ocean songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Frank Ocean]]\n", "name_user": "Richboythebeast", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed category text at the top", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dear_April"}
{"title_page": "Trevor Cope", "text_new": "'''Anthony Trevor Cope''' was professor of [[Zulu language|Zulu]] at the [[University of Natal]]. He edited [[Harry Camp Lugg]]'s translation of [[Magema Magwaza Fuze]]'s ''Abantu Abamnyama'' (1922) into English which was published by the University of Natal Press in 1979 as ''The Black People and Whence They Came''.<ref name=camp>[http://campbell.ukzn.ac.za/?q=taxonomy/term/358 Fuze, Magema Magwaza /Papers.] Campbell Collections, University of KwaZulu-Natal. Retrieved 3 August 2018.</ref><ref name=\"oxf\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=39JMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA403 \"Fuze, Magema\"] by Hlonipha Mokoena in {{cite book|author=[[Emmanuel Kwaku Akyeampong]] & [[Henry Louis Gates Jr.]] (Eds.)|title=Dictionary of African Biography|url=|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press. Vol. 2|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-538207-5|pages=403\u2013405}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Izibongo. Zulu praise-poems''. Collected by [[James Stuart (linguist)|James Stuart]]. Translated by [[D. McK Malcolm|Daniel Malcolm]]. Edited with introductions and annotations by Anthony Trevor Cope. Clarendon Press, Oxford, 1968.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rycroft|first=David|date=1969|title=Review of Izibongo: Zulu Praise-Poems Collected by|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London|volume=32|issue=2|pages=438\u2013441|jstor=614051|doi=10.1017/S0041977X00055798}}</ref>\n* ''A Select Bibliography Relating to the Zulu People of Natal and Zululand''. l974.\n* ''A Comprehensive Course in the Zulu Language''. University of Natal, 1982.\n* ''The Black People and Whence They Came''. Magema Magwaza Fuze, translated by Harry Camp Lugg and edited by Anthony Trevor Cope. University of Natal Press, Pietermaritzburg, 1979. (Killie Campbell Africana library. Translation series, No. 1) {{ISBN|0869801678}}\n* ''Zulu Phonology, Tonology and Tonal Grammar''. 1986.\n* ''UMamazane = Mamazane''. R.H. Mthembu, translated into English by D.M. Mzolo and Anthony Trevor Cope. Solo Collective, Cowies Hill, South Africa, 2003.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cope, Trevor}}\n[[Category:University of Natal faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:South African translators]]\n[[Category:Zulu language]]\n[[Category:Zulu-language writers]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Anthony Trevor Cope''' was professor of [[Zulu language|Zulu]] at the [[University of Natal]]. He edited [[Harry Camp Lugg]]'s translation of [[Magema Magwaza Fuze]]'s ''Abantu Abamnyama'' (1922) into English which was published by the University of Natal Press in 1979 as ''The Black People and Whence They Came''.<ref name=camp>[http://campbell.ukzn.ac.za/?q=taxonomy/term/358 Fuze, Magema Magwaza /Papers.] Campbell Collections, University of KwaZulu-Natal. Retrieved 3 August 2018.</ref><ref name=\"oxf\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=39JMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA403 \"Fuze, Magema\"] by Hlonipha Mokoena in {{cite book|author=[[Emmanuel Kwaku Akyeampong]] & [[Henry Louis Gates Jr.]] (Eds.)|title=Dictionary of African Biography|url=|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press. Vol. 2|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-538207-5|pages=403\u2013405}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Izibongo. Zulu praise-poems''. Collected by [[James Stuart (linguist)|James Stuart]]. Translated by [[D. McK Malcolm|Daniel Malcolm]]. Edited with introductions and annotations by Anthony Trevor Cope. Clarendon Press, Oxford, 1968.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rycroft|first=David|date=1969|title=Review of Izibongo: Zulu Praise-Poems Collected by|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London|volume=32|issue=2|pages=438\u2013441|jstor=614051|doi=10.1017/S0041977X00055798}}</ref>\n* ''A Select Bibliography Relating to the Zulu People of Natal and Zululand''. l974.\n* ''A Comprehensive Course in the Zulu 