{"title_page": "Inner Terai Valleys of Nepal", "text_new": "The '''Inner [[Terai]] Valleys of [[Nepal]]''' ({{lang-ne|\u092d\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u092e\u0927\u0947\u0936}}) comprise several elongated river valleys in the southern lowland Terai part of the country. These [[tropical]] valleys are enclosed by the [[Himalaya]]n foothills, viz the [[Mahabharat Range]] and the [[Sivalik Hills]] farther south.<ref name=Nagendra>{{cite journal |author=Nagendra, H. |year=2002 |title=Tenure and forest conditions: community forestry in the Nepal '''Terai''' |journal=Environmental Conservation |issue=29 (04) |pages=530\u2013539}}</ref>\nThe Inner Terai is called \"bhitri Terai \" in Nepali language.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gurung, H. |year=1971 |title=Landscape pattern of Nepal |journal=Himalayan Review |issue=4 |pages=1\u201310}}</ref>\n\nThe Inner Terai Valleys are part of the [[Terai-Duar savanna and grasslands]] [[ecoregion]].<ref name=im0701>Dinerstein, E., Loucks, C. (2001). {{WWF ecoregion|name=Terai-Duar savanna and grasslands|id=im0701}}</ref> They are filled up with coarse to fine [[alluvial]] [[sediments]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hasegawa S., Dahal R. K., Yamanaka M., Bhandary N. P., Yatabe R., Inagaki H. | year = 2009 | title = Causes of large-scale landslides in the Lesser Himalaya of central Nepal | url = | journal = Environmental Geology | volume = 57 | issue = 6| pages = 1423\u20131434 | doi=10.1007/s00254-008-1420-z}}</ref> The [[Chitwan Valley]] and the [[Dang Valley|Dang]] and [[Deukhuri Valley]]s are some of the largest Inner Terai Valleys. [[Malaria]] was prevalent in this region until the late 1950s. Since its eradication, the area became a viable destination for large-scale migration of people from the hills, who transformed the area from [[virgin forest]] and grassland to farmland.<ref name=\"Grung1988\">Gurung, H. (1988). Nepal: Consequences of migration and policy implications. Contributions to Nepalese Studies 15 (1): 67\u201394.</ref>\n\n==Geology==\n[[Image:2_2_himal_tecto_units.png|thumb|'''Fig 5:''' Geologic \u2013 Tectonic map of the Himalaya, modified after Le Fort (1988).]]\n{{main|Geology of the Himalaya}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2014}}\n\nThe [[Himalayas]] were formed by the collision of the Indian sub-continent with [[Eurasia]], which began about 50 million years ago   and continues today.  The [[oceanic crust]] in front of India slid under Eurasia, pushing up the [[Tibetan plateau]]. The Indian [[continental crust]] is also pushing under Tibet, but is partly compressed and thrust upward to form the Himalayan mountain range, extending for over 2400&nbsp;km and rising as high as 8848 m at Mt. [[Everest]] Chomolungma.\n\nThe Himalayas have four [[tectonic]] subdivisions:\n\n* The Indus Suture Zone, where the Indian Plate meets the Eurasian Transhimalaya or Karakoram-Lhasa Block.\n* The Central Himalayan Domain, the high backbone of the Himalayas bounded on the south by a fault zone called the MCT (Main Central Thrust) that has elevated these peaks three or four thousand meters above lower ranges to the south.\n* The \"middle hills\" below the MCT south to the Lesser Himalaya or Mahabharat Range which is bounded by another fault zone, the MBT (Main Boundary Thrust) that abruptly elevates the Mahabharats 1,000 to 2,000 meters above hills further south.\n* The Sub-himalaya also known as the Muree, Chure Hills or [[Siwaliks]], which are the southernmost foothills of the Himalayan Range and mainly composed of folded and overlapping sheets of sediment from the erosion of the Himalaya.  They are bounded on the south by the HFT (Himalayan Frontal Thrust) elevating them about 500 meters above the [[Gangetic plain]].\n\nThe Inner Terai valleys lie between the Siwalik and Mahabharat ranges or sometimes between different ranges in the Siwaliks. They hold flat plains with winding rivers that shift course from time to time, running northwest or southeast along the axis of the Siwalik ranges until they find a break and flow  into the Outer Terai and [[Gangetic plain]].  Usually there is little difference in elevation between the Inner Terai valley floors and the plains of the Outer Terai.\n\n==Climate==\n[[Image:Nepal topo en.jpg|thumb|400px|right|Nepal topography. The green/yellow zones hold the Inner Terai valleys.]]\n\nThe [[Terai]] has a humid, [[subtropic]]al climate. The mean annual rainfall at the Rampur weatherstation in Chitwan was {{convert|2214|mm|in|abbr=on}} between 1995 and 2006. More than 80% of the total annual rainfall occurs during the [[monsoon]] season from June to September. Average temperatures ranged from {{convert|8.08|C|F|abbr=on}} in January to {{convert|34.91|C|F|abbr=on}} in June.<ref>Department of Hydrology and Meteorology (2006). Climatological Records of Nepal (Several Volumes), Babarmahal, Kathmandu.</ref>\n\nIn the past, the inner and outer Terai were a formidable barrier between Nepal and potential invaders from India because marshes and forests were infested by [[Anopheles|anopheline mosquitos]] that transmitted virulent strains of [[malaria]], especially during the hot spring and rainy summer monsoon.\n\n== History ==\nUntil the mid 18th century, the Terai was divided into several smaller kingdoms, and the forests were little disturbed.<ref name=Gautam2004>Gautam, A. P., Shivakoti, G. P., & Webb, E. L. (2004). A review of forest policies, institutions, and changes in the resource condition in Nepal. International Forestry Review 6 (2): 136\u2013148.</ref> After the [[unification of Nepal]] in the late 1760s, the rulers granted large areas of fertiIe land and forest resources to members of the royal family, officials, priests and selected groups of the society. The beneficiaries of these grants had the right to collect revenues from cultivated land and forest products. They appointed tax collectors who were also responsible for reclamation of land and establishment of settlements.<ref name=Regmi1994>Regmi, R. R. (1994). Deforestation and Rural Society in the Nepalese Terai. Occasional Papers in Sociology and Anthropology 4: 72\u201389.</ref>\nIn the late 1920s, the [[Rana dynasty|Rana]] rulers ordered the clearing of forests and extraction of timber for export to India in order to collect revenues. Cleared areas were subsequently used for agriculture.<ref name=Gautam2004/>\n\n[[Tharu people]] have been living in the Terai for many centuries, and reputedly had an innate resistance to [[malaria]].<ref name=\"terrenato88\">{{Cite journal |author=Terrenato, L., Shrestha, S., Dixit, K.A., Luzzatto, L., Modiano, G., Morpurgo, G., Arese, P. |title=Decreased malaria morbidity in the Tharu people compared to sympatric populations in Nepal |journal=Annals of Tropical Medicine and Parasitology |volume=82 |issue=1 |year=1988 |pages=1\u201311 |pmid=3041928 |doi=10.1080/00034983.1988.11812202}}</ref>\nAfter malaria was eradicated using [[DDT]] in the mid 1950s, people from the hills migrated to the Terai. Timber export continued to 1969. In 1970, the [[King Mahendra|king]] granted land to loyal ex-army personnel in the districts of [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]], [[Sunsari District|Sunsari]], [[Rupandehi District|Rupandehi]] and [[Banke District|Banke]], where seven colonies were developed for resettling about 7,000 people. They acquired property rights over uncultivated forest and waste land, thus accelerating the deforestation process in the Terai.<ref name=Regmi1994/>\n\n== Economy ==\nBoth Inner and Outer Terai have become Nepal's richest economic regions, with fertile farms and forests because of the area's generally flat terrain that is drained and nourished by several rivers. The Terai also has the largest commercially exploitable forests.\n\n==Environmental Issues==\nThe well-meaning malaria eradication campaign has had unexpected consequences by opening up the Terai region to human settlement.  The Inner Terai valleys are home to a rich and diverse ecosystem. Since the early 1990s, however, the forests have been increasingly destroyed because of growing demands for timber and agricultural land<ref>[http://www.forestrynepal.org/publications/reports/3778 Regional Workshop on Issues, Challenges and Opportunities for Forest Management of Terai, Inner Terai and Churia in Nepal]</ref><ref>[http://www.forestsmonitor.org/en/reports/549391/549398 Forests Monitor: The Terai Forests]</ref>\nThis has led to concerns about the risk of losing many rare plant,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mountainfund.org/html_site/research/orchids_in_the_churiya_hills_and_their_survival_in_nepal.pdf |title=Orchids in the Churiya Hills and their survival in Nepal |access-date=2008-10-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219183024/http://www.mountainfund.org/html_site/research/orchids_in_the_churiya_hills_and_their_survival_in_nepal.pdf |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nepjol.info/index.php/ON/article/viewFile/506/506 An Overview of Floral Diversity in Wetlands of Terai Region of Nepal: M. Siwakoti, Natural History Museum, Tribhuvan University Swayambhu, Nepal]</ref> animal and insect species.\n\nThe valleys also mitigate the severity of floods on the [[Gangetic plains]]. During heavy rainfall forests absorb water.  During floods, rivers overflow their banks and flood adjacent forests. Later the forests gradually release water back into the rivers.  Deforestation reduces this buffering effect. It also accelerates soil erosion, causing downstream rivers to silt up and overflow their banks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://home.iitk.ac.in/~rsinha/Vik_syn.htm |title=Fluvial geomorphological analysis with special reference to flood hazard, Baghmati River basin, north Bihar, India |access-date=2008-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922005356/http://home.iitk.ac.in/~rsinha/Vik_syn.htm |archive-date=2008-09-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The frequency and severity of flooding in the Gangetic plain and Bangladesh has steadily increased in recent years. Deforestation of the Terai appears to be one of the major causes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cs.albany.edu/~amit/BanglaFloods.txt |title=RECENT FLOODS IN BANGLADESH: POSSIBLE CAUSES AND SOLUTIONS |access-date=2008-10-14 |archive-url=https://archive.is/19970724184800/http://www.cs.albany.edu/~amit/BanglaFloods.txt |archive-date=1997-07-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Indian and Nepalese governments are cooperating in measures including construction of barrages and dams in the Terai, such as the [[Koshi Barrage]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wrmin.nic.in/writereaddata/linkimages/flood%20and%20centrally%20sponsered%20schemes2735345443.pdf |title=Indian Ministry of Water Resources \u2013 Flood and centrally sponsored schemes (c) |access-date=2008-10-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219184550/http://wrmin.nic.in/writereaddata/linkimages/flood%20and%20centrally%20sponsered%20schemes2735345443.pdf |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, these efforts may have mixed results.  They contain floodwater in the short term, but may increase the problem in the longer term by reducing water velocity in the rivers downstream, and thus accelerating silting and reducing the drainage capacity of the rivers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hewett.norfolk.sch.uk/CURRIC/NEWGEOG/floods/floodreport.htm |title=Causes, Effects and responses to flooding: The UK and Bangladesh |access-date=2008-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121193126/http://www.hewett.norfolk.sch.uk/curric/NEWGEOG/floods/floodreport.htm |archive-date=2009-01-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Valleys==\nThe major Inner Terai Valleys are listed from west to east.\nClick on the terrain and satellite imagery links to see vegetation, rivers, topography, roads and towns.\n\n===Western Terai===\nMarkers at valleys ''Jogbudha'' ('''J'''), ''Surkhet'' ('''S'''), ''Dang'' ('''A''') and ''Deukhuri'' ('''E''') [https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.4011,81.4196&zoom%3D8&size%3D640x400&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:J%7C29.1354,80.3362&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:S%7C28.5791,81.6219&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.4011,81.4196&zoom%3D8&size%3D640x400&maptype%3Dsatellite&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:J%7C29.1354,80.3362&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:S%7C28.5791,81.6219&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n<!-- ====Jogbuda Valley====\n[[File:NepalDadeldhuraDistrictmap.png|thumb|Map of the [[Village development committee (Nepal)|VDC]]s in Dadeldhura District]]\nThe [[Jogbuda]] Valley ({{lang-ne|\u091c\u094b\u0917\u092c\u0941\u0922\u093e \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) is a small valley in the south of the [[Dadeldhura district]], [[Mahakali zone]] in Nepal's [[Far Western Region, Nepal|far western region]]. Streams empty into the Mahakali or [[Sarda River]] which rises in the high Himalaya and defines most of Nepal's western border with [[Uttarakhand]], India.\n\nImagery of ''Jogbuda'' valley ('''J'''):\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D29.1354,80.3362&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:J%7C29.1354,80.3362&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D29.11,80.34&zoom%3D12&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dsatellite&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\nLocated in the Outer Terai south of this valley is the [[Suklaphanta Wildlife Reserve]], home of the largest herd of [[Barasingha|swamp deer]] in the world. In 1984 [[UNESCO]] listed it as a [[World Heritage Site]].<ref name=nbrb2007/> -->\n\n====Surkhet Valley====\n[[Image:NepalSurkhetDistrictmap.png|thumb|Map of the VDCs in Surkhet District]]\nThe Surkhet Valley ({{lang-ne|\u0938\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0916\u0947\u0924 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) is situated in the [[Surkhet district]], [[Mid Western Region, Nepal|mid-western Nepal]]. The valley is about {{convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level, forming an ellipse about {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} east-west by {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-south. It is drained by the [[Bheri River]], a tributary of the [[Karnali River|Karnali]].<ref>Yadav, S. K. (2002). [http://www.ub.uib.no/elpub/NORAD/2002/ntnu/thesis01.pdf Hydrological Analysis for Bheri-Babai Hydropower Project Nepal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219183024/http://www.ub.uib.no/elpub/NORAD/2002/ntnu/thesis01.pdf |date=2008-12-19 }}. MSc. Thesis, The Norwegian University For Science and Technology, Trondheim.</ref>\nThe district is the homeland of the [[Raji people]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Thapa L. B., Dhakal T. M., Chaudhary R., Thapa H. | year = 2014 | title = Medicinal Plants Used by Raji Ethnic Tribe of Nepal in Treatment of Gastrointestinal Disorders | url = | journal = Our Nature | volume = 11 | issue = 2| pages = 177\u2013186 | doi = 10.3126/on.v11i2.9645 }}</ref> Tharu people from Dang settled in the valley since at least the 19th century.<ref name=Krauskopff1995>{{cite journal | author = Krauskopff G | year = 1995 | title = The Anthropology of the Tharus: An Annotated Bibliography | url = | journal = A Journal of Himalayan Studies | volume = 17 | issue = 3&4| pages = 185\u2013213 }}</ref>\nIn recent decades there has been increased migration from surrounding mountain districts as well as other parts of the country. [[Birendranagar]] is the district's capital.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nImagery of ''Surkhet'' ('''S'''):\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.35,81.6219&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x640&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:S%7C28.5791,81.6219&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.5791,81.6219&zoom%3D12&size%3D640x640&maptype%3Dsatellite&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\n====Dang and Deukhuri Valleys====\n[[File:NepalDangDistrictmap.png|thumb|Map of the settlements in Dang-Deukhuri District]]\nBoth valleys are located in the [[Dang Deukhuri District]] of the [[Rapti Zone]] in mid-western Nepal.<ref name=Krauskopff1995/>\nThe Dang Valley ({{lang-ne|\u0926\u093e\u0919 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) lies between the Mahabharat Range in the north and the Churia Range in the south.<ref>Sharmai, D. R. (1988). Archaeological Remains of the Dang Valley. Ancient Nepal 88: 8\u201315.</ref> It forms a\nnearly {{convert|1000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} plain within a local drainage basin of less than {{convert|3000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. It is drained by the [[Babai River]], and is one of the largest Inner Terai valleys.<ref name=Mugnier>{{cite journal | author = Mugnier J. L., Leturmy P., Mascle G., Huyghe P., Chalaron E., Vidal G., Delcaillau B. | year = 1999 | title = The Siwaliks of western Nepal: I. Geometry and kinematics | url = | journal = Journal of Asian Earth Sciences | volume = 17 | issue = 5| pages = 629\u2013642 | doi=10.1016/s1367-9120(99)00038-3}}</ref>\n[[Ghorahi]] is the largest city and the administrative, economical and educational center of Dang District.It has a fair weather airport with code DNG. Other towns in the valley include Tulsipur, Tripur and Laxmipur. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nThe Deukhuri Valley ({{lang-ne|\u0926\u0947\u0909\u0916\u0941\u0930\u0940 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) is southeast of the Dang Valley and extends about {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} in WNW-ESE direction with a maximum width of {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Kimura>Kimura, K. (1998). Geomorphic Development of the Deukhuri Dun, Nepal Sub-Himalaya. The science reports of the Tohoku University, 7th series.</ref> It forms a nearly {{convert|600|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} plain within a drainage basin of {{convert|6100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Mugnier/> The valley is drained by the [[West Rapti River]].<ref name=Kimura/> It emerges from its gorge through the Mahabharat Range and flows WNW along the axis of the Siwalik Range between the [[Dundwa Range]] along the India border and the Dang subrange to the north. It flows {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} in this direction until the Dundwas fall away near [[Banke District|Banke]], and the river can resume flowing SE toward the [[Ganges]].{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nThe [[Mahendra Highway]] passes through the Deukhuri Valley.<ref name=Mugnier/> Both valleys are settled by Tharu people,<ref name=Krauskopff1995/> and used as winter pasture by [[Kham Magar]] from the hills.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nImagery of Dang ('''A''') and Deukhuri ('''E'''): \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.9471,82.4538&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] [https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.9471,82.4538&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dsatellite&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\n===Central Terai===\n\n====Chitwan Valley====\n[[Image:Narayani districts.png|thumb|Narayani zone: the Chitwan district is marked in yellow]]\n\nThe [[Chitwan Valley]] ({{lang-ne|\u091a\u093f\u0924\u0935\u0928 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) encompasses the districts of [[Nawalpur District|Nawalpur]], [[Chitwan District|Chitwan]] and [[Makwanpur District|Makwanpur]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of central Nepal. It is {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and roughly {{convert|30-48|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide.\nThe cities of [[Bharatpur, Nepal|Bharatpur]], [[Ratnanagar]] and [[Hetauda]] are in the valley. It is drained by the [[East Rapti River|Rapti River]] flowing from the Mahabharat Range near Hetauda, then west down the valley to join the [[Narayani River]] west of [[Meghauli]]. The Narayani is also called Gandaki further upstream and Gandak in India.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nImagery of ''Chitwan'' ('''C'''):\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.45,84.44&zoom%3D9&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:C%7C27.57,84.49&sensor%3Dfalse terrain]\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.59,84.42&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x350&maptype%3Dsatellite&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\nThe [[Chitwan National Park]], Nepal's first national park established in 1973, was declared a World Heritage site by UNESCO in 1984. It contains the largest and least disturbed natural [[Shorea robusta|Sal]] hill forest and associated communities. Its fauna comprises [[Bengal tiger]], [[Indian leopard]], [[Indian Rhinoceros|great one-horned rhinos]], wild [[Asian elephant]], [[gaur]], golden [[monitor lizard]], [[gharial]] and [[marsh crocodile]].<ref name=nbrb2007/>\n\n===Eastern Terai===\n====Kamala Valley====\n[[Image:Sagarmatha districts.png|thumb|right|Sagarmatha zone: Udayapur district in green]] \nThe Kamala Valley, also called Udayapur Valley ({{lang-ne|'''\u0915\u092e\u0932\u093e''' or '''\u0909\u0926\u092f\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e'''}}) is in [[Udayapur district]] in southeastern Nepal ([http://ncthakur.itgo.com/districtmaps/udayapur_district.htm Sketch map]). It is about {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and between {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} and {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide. It is drained by the Triyuga river flowing east to join the great [[Koshi River|Koshi]]. This valley lies between the Mahabharat Range to the north and the [[Sivalik Hills]] to the south, with an average elevation of about {{convert|430|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>Darsie, Jr, R. F., Pradhan, S. P., & Vaidya, R. G. (1992). [http://www.mosquitocatalog.org/pdfs/MS24N01P023.Pdf Notes on the mosquitoes of Nepal: II. New species records from 1991 collections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219183024/http://www.mosquitocatalog.org/pdfs/MS24N01P023.Pdf |date=2008-12-19 }}. Mosquito Systematics 24: 23\u201328.</ref> [[Triyuga]] is the main town.\n\nThe mouth of the valley opens onto a {{convert|175|km|mi|abbr=on}} rectangle of land where the Triyuga meets the Koshi river above the [[Kosi embankment|Koshi Barrage]]. It was designated the [[Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve]] in 1976, and is home to the last remaining population of [[wild Asian water buffalo]] in Nepal. The reserve is mostly wetlands, subject to seasonal flooding, but also includes some grasslands and small patches of riverine forest. It is a [[Ramsar Site]].<ref name=nbrb2007>{{Cite book|author=Bhuju, U. R., Shakya, P. R., Basnet, T. B., Shrestha, S. |title=Nepal Biodiversity Resource Book. Protected Areas, Ramsar Sites, and World Heritage Sites |place=Kathmandu |publisher=International Centre for Integrated Mountain Development; Government of Nepal, Ministry of Environment, Science and Technology; United Nations Environment Programme, Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific |year=2007 |url=http://books.icimod.org/demo/uploads/ftp/Nepal%20Biodiversity%20Resource%20Book.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726170342/http://books.icimod.org/demo/uploads/ftp/Nepal%20Biodiversity%20Resource%20Book.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nImagery of Kamala valley:\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D26.8,86.85&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x640&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:K%7C26.7824,86.7947&sensor%3Dfalse terrain]\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D26.8,86.85&zoom%3D10&size%3D480x480&maptype%3Dsatellite&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:K%7C26.7824,86.7947&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\nTraditionally, the Kamala Valley was primarily inhabited by the [[Dhanwar Rai language|Dhanwar]] people (or Danuwar),<ref>Khatry, P. (1995). [http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/contributions/CNAS_22_01_04.pdf The Manjani System of the Danuwar State of the Kamala Valley: A Brief Study of an Egalitarian Judiciary]. Contributions to Nepalese Studies 22 (1): 43\u201355.</ref> but there is a fast-growing population of migrants from the Nepali hills and from India.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inner Terai Valleys of Nepal}}\n[[Category:Valleys of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Terai-Duar savanna and grasslands]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Grasslands of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Plains of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Wetlands of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Bheri Zone]]\n[[Category:Janakpur Zone]]\n[[Category:Karnali Zone]]\n[[Category:Rapti Zone]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Inner [[Terai]] Valleys of [[Nepal]]''' ({{lang-ne|\u092d\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u092e\u0927\u0947\u0936}}) comprise several elongated river valleys in the southern lowland Terai part of the country. These [[tropical]] valleys are enclosed by the [[Himalaya]]n foothills, viz the [[Mahabharat Range]] and the [[Sivalik Hills]] farther south.<ref name=Nagendra>{{cite journal |author=Nagendra, H. |year=2002 |title=Tenure and forest conditions: community forestry in the Nepal '''Terai''' |journal=Environmental Conservation |issue=29 (04) |pages=530\u2013539}}</ref>\nThe Inner Terai is called \"bhitri Terai \" in Nepali language.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gurung, H. |year=1971 |title=Landscape pattern of Nepal |journal=Himalayan Review |issue=4 |pages=1\u201310}}</ref>\n\nThe Inner Terai Valleys are part of the [[Terai-Duar savanna and grasslands]] [[ecoregion]].<ref name=im0701>Dinerstein, E., Loucks, C. (2001). {{WWF ecoregion|name=Terai-Duar savanna and grasslands|id=im0701}}</ref> They are filled up with coarse to fine [[alluvial]] [[sediments]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hasegawa S., Dahal R. K., Yamanaka M., Bhandary N. P., Yatabe R., Inagaki H. | year = 2009 | title = Causes of large-scale landslides in the Lesser Himalaya of central Nepal | url = | journal = Environmental Geology | volume = 57 | issue = 6| pages = 1423\u20131434 | doi=10.1007/s00254-008-1420-z}}</ref> The [[Chitwan Valley]] and the [[Dang Valley|Dang]] and [[Deukhuri Valley]]s are some of the largest Inner Terai Valleys. [[Malaria]] was prevalent in this region until the late 1950s. Since its eradication, the area became a viable destination for large-scale migration of people from the hills, who transformed the area from [[virgin forest]] and grassland to farmland.<ref name=\"Grung1988\">Gurung, H. (1988). Nepal: Consequences of migration and policy implications. Contributions to Nepalese Studies 15 (1): 67\u201394.</ref>\n\n==Geology==\n[[Image:2_2_himal_tecto_units.png|thumb|'''Fig 5:''' Geologic \u2013 Tectonic map of the Himalaya, modified after Le Fort (1988).]]\n{{main|Geology of the Himalaya}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2014}}\n\nThe [[Himalayas]] were formed by the collision of the Indian sub-continent with [[Eurasia]], which began about 50 million years ago   and continues today.  The [[oceanic crust]] in front of India slid under Eurasia, pushing up the [[Tibetan plateau]]. The Indian [[continental crust]] is also pushing under Tibet, but is partly compressed and thrust upward to form the Himalayan mountain range, extending for over 2400&nbsp;km and rising as high as 8848 m at Mt. [[Everest]] Chomolungma.\n\nThe Himalayas have four [[tectonic]] subdivisions:\n\n* The Indus Suture Zone, where the Indian Plate meets the Eurasian Transhimalaya or Karakoram-Lhasa Block.\n* The Central Himalayan Domain, the high backbone of the Himalayas bounded on the south by a fault zone called the MCT (Main Central Thrust) that has elevated these peaks three or four thousand meters above lower ranges to the south.\n* The \"middle hills\" below the MCT south to the Lesser Himalaya or Mahabharat Range which is bounded by another fault zone, the MBT (Main Boundary Thrust) that abruptly elevates the Mahabharats 1,000 to 2,000 meters above hills further south.\n* The Sub-himalaya also known as the Muree, Chure Hills or [[Siwaliks]], which are the southernmost foothills of the Himalayan Range and mainly composed of folded and overlapping sheets of sediment from the erosion of the Himalaya.  They are bounded on the south by the HFT (Himalayan Frontal Thrust) elevating them about 500 meters above the [[Gangetic plain]].\n\nThe Inner Terai valleys lie between the Siwalik and Mahabharat ranges or sometimes between different ranges in the Siwaliks. They hold flat plains with winding rivers that shift course from time to time, running northwest or southeast along the axis of the Siwalik ranges until they find a break and flow  into the Outer Terai and [[Gangetic plain]].  Usually there is little difference in elevation between the Inner Terai valley floors and the plains of the Outer Terai.\n\n==Climate==\n[[Image:Nepal topo en.jpg|thumb|400px|right|Nepal topography. The green/yellow zones hold the Inner Terai valleys.]]\n\nThe [[Terai]] has a humid, [[subtropic]]al climate. The mean annual rainfall at the Rampur weatherstation in Chitwan was {{convert|2214|mm|in|abbr=on}} between 1995 and 2006. More than 80% of the total annual rainfall occurs during the [[monsoon]] season from June to September. Average temperatures ranged from {{convert|8.08|C|F|abbr=on}} in January to {{convert|34.91|C|F|abbr=on}} in June.<ref>Department of Hydrology and Meteorology (2006). Climatological Records of Nepal (Several Volumes), Babarmahal, Kathmandu.</ref>\n\nIn the past, the inner and outer Terai were a formidable barrier between Nepal and potential invaders from India because marshes and forests were infested by [[Anopheles|anopheline mosquitos]] that transmitted virulent strains of [[malaria]], especially during the hot spring and rainy summer monsoon.\n\n== History ==\nUntil the mid 18th century, the Terai was divided into several smaller kingdoms, and the forests were little disturbed.<ref name=Gautam2004>Gautam, A. P., Shivakoti, G. P., & Webb, E. L. (2004). A review of forest policies, institutions, and changes in the resource condition in Nepal. International Forestry Review 6 (2): 136\u2013148.</ref> After the [[unification of Nepal]] in the late 1760s, the rulers granted large areas of fertiIe land and forest resources to members of the royal family, officials, priests and selected groups of the society. The beneficiaries of these grants had the right to collect revenues from cultivated land and forest products. They appointed tax collectors who were also responsible for reclamation of land and establishment of settlements.<ref name=Regmi1994>Regmi, R. R. (1994). Deforestation and Rural Society in the Nepalese Terai. Occasional Papers in Sociology and Anthropology 4: 72\u201389.</ref>\nIn the late 1920s, the [[Rana dynasty|Rana]] rulers ordered the clearing of forests and extraction of timber for export to India in order to collect revenues. Cleared areas were subsequently used for agriculture.<ref name=Gautam2004/>\n\n[[Tharu people]] have been living in the Terai for many centuries, and reputedly had an innate resistance to [[malaria]].<ref name=\"terrenato88\">{{Cite journal |author=Terrenato, L., Shrestha, S., Dixit, K.A., Luzzatto, L., Modiano, G., Morpurgo, G., Arese, P. |title=Decreased malaria morbidity in the Tharu people compared to sympatric populations in Nepal |journal=Annals of Tropical Medicine and Parasitology |volume=82 |issue=1 |year=1988 |pages=1\u201311 |pmid=3041928 |doi=10.1080/00034983.1988.11812202}}</ref>\nAfter malaria was eradicated using [[DDT]] in the mid 1950s, people from the hills migrated to the Terai. Timber export continued to 1969. In 1970, the [[King Mahendra|king]] granted land to loyal ex-army personnel in the districts of [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]], [[Sunsari District|Sunsari]], [[Rupandehi District|Rupandehi]] and [[Banke District|Banke]], where seven colonies were developed for resettling about 7,000 people. They acquired property rights over uncultivated forest and waste land, thus accelerating the deforestation process in the Terai.<ref name=Regmi1994/>\n\n== Economy ==\nBoth Inner and Outer Terai have become Nepal's richest economic regions, with fertile farms and forests because of the area's generally flat terrain that is drained and nourished by several rivers. The Terai also has the largest commercially exploitable forests.\n\n==Environmental Issues==\nThe well-meaning malaria eradication campaign has had unexpected consequences by opening up the Terai region to human settlement.  The Inner Terai valleys are home to a rich and diverse ecosystem. Since the early 1990s, however, the forests have been increasingly destroyed because of growing demands for timber and agricultural land<ref>[http://www.forestrynepal.org/publications/reports/3778 Regional Workshop on Issues, Challenges and Opportunities for Forest Management of Terai, Inner Terai and Churia in Nepal]</ref><ref>[http://www.forestsmonitor.org/en/reports/549391/549398 Forests Monitor: The Terai Forests]</ref>\nThis has led to concerns about the risk of losing many rare plant,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mountainfund.org/html_site/research/orchids_in_the_churiya_hills_and_their_survival_in_nepal.pdf |title=Orchids in the Churiya Hills and their survival in Nepal |access-date=2008-10-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219183024/http://www.mountainfund.org/html_site/research/orchids_in_the_churiya_hills_and_their_survival_in_nepal.pdf |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nepjol.info/index.php/ON/article/viewFile/506/506 An Overview of Floral Diversity in Wetlands of Terai Region of Nepal: M. Siwakoti, Natural History Museum, Tribhuvan University Swayambhu, Nepal]</ref> animal and insect species.\n\nThe valleys also mitigate the severity of floods on the [[Gangetic plains]]. During heavy rainfall forests absorb water.  During floods, rivers overflow their banks and flood adjacent forests. Later the forests gradually release water back into the rivers.  Deforestation reduces this buffering effect. It also accelerates soil erosion, causing downstream rivers to silt up and overflow their banks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://home.iitk.ac.in/~rsinha/Vik_syn.htm |title=Fluvial geomorphological analysis with special reference to flood hazard, Baghmati River basin, north Bihar, India |access-date=2008-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922005356/http://home.iitk.ac.in/~rsinha/Vik_syn.htm |archive-date=2008-09-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The frequency and severity of flooding in the Gangetic plain and Bangladesh has steadily increased in recent years. Deforestation of the Terai appears to be one of the major causes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cs.albany.edu/~amit/BanglaFloods.txt |title=RECENT FLOODS IN BANGLADESH: POSSIBLE CAUSES AND SOLUTIONS |access-date=2008-10-14 |archive-url=https://archive.is/19970724184800/http://www.cs.albany.edu/~amit/BanglaFloods.txt |archive-date=1997-07-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Indian and Nepalese governments are cooperating in measures including construction of barrages and dams in the Terai, such as the [[Koshi Barrage]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wrmin.nic.in/writereaddata/linkimages/flood%20and%20centrally%20sponsered%20schemes2735345443.pdf |title=Indian Ministry of Water Resources \u2013 Flood and centrally sponsored schemes (c) |access-date=2008-10-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219184550/http://wrmin.nic.in/writereaddata/linkimages/flood%20and%20centrally%20sponsered%20schemes2735345443.pdf |archive-date=2008-12-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, these efforts may have mixed results.  They contain floodwater in the short term, but may increase the problem in the longer term by reducing water velocity in the rivers downstream, and thus accelerating silting and reducing the drainage capacity of the rivers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hewett.norfolk.sch.uk/CURRIC/NEWGEOG/floods/floodreport.htm |title=Causes, Effects and responses to flooding: The UK and Bangladesh |access-date=2008-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121193126/http://www.hewett.norfolk.sch.uk/curric/NEWGEOG/floods/floodreport.htm |archive-date=2009-01-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Valleys==\nThe major Inner Terai Valleys are listed from west to east.\nClick on the terrain and satellite imagery links to see vegetation, rivers, topography, roads and towns.\n\n===Western Terai===\nMarkers at valleys ''Jogbudha'' ('''J'''), ''Surkhet'' ('''S'''), ''Dang'' ('''A''') and ''Deukhuri'' ('''E''') [https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.4011,81.4196&zoom%3D8&size%3D640x400&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:J%7C29.1354,80.3362&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:S%7C28.5791,81.6219&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.4011,81.4196&zoom%3D8&size%3D640x400&maptype%3Dsatellite&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:J%7C29.1354,80.3362&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:S%7C28.5791,81.6219&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n<!-- ====Jogbuda Valley====\n[[File:NepalDadeldhuraDistrictmap.png|thumb|Map of the [[Village development committee (Nepal)|VDC]]s in Dadeldhura District]]\nThe [[Jogbuda]] Valley ({{lang-ne|\u091c\u094b\u0917\u092c\u0941\u0922\u093e \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) is a small valley in the south of the [[Dadeldhura district]], [[Mahakali zone]] in Nepal's [[Far Western Region, Nepal|far western region]]. Streams empty into the Mahakali or [[Sarda River]] which rises in the high Himalaya and defines most of Nepal's western border with [[Uttarakhand]], India.\n\nImagery of ''Jogbuda'' valley ('''J'''):\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D29.1354,80.3362&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:J%7C29.1354,80.3362&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D29.11,80.34&zoom%3D12&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dsatellite&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\nLocated in the Outer Terai south of this valley is the [[Suklaphanta Wildlife Reserve]], home of the largest herd of [[Barasingha|swamp deer]] in the world. In 1984 [[UNESCO]] listed it as a [[World Heritage Site]].<ref name=nbrb2007/> -->\n\n====Surkhet Valley====\n[[Image:NepalSurkhetDistrictmap.png|thumb|Map of the VDCs in Surkhet District]]\nThe Surkhet Valley ({{lang-ne|\u0938\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0916\u0947\u0924 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) is situated in the [[Surkhet district]], [[Mid Western Region, Nepal|mid-western Nepal]]. The valley is about {{convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level, forming an ellipse about {{convert|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} east-west by {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-south. It is drained by the [[Bheri River]], a tributary of the [[Karnali River|Karnali]].<ref>Yadav, S. K. (2002). [http://www.ub.uib.no/elpub/NORAD/2002/ntnu/thesis01.pdf Hydrological Analysis for Bheri-Babai Hydropower Project Nepal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219183024/http://www.ub.uib.no/elpub/NORAD/2002/ntnu/thesis01.pdf |date=2008-12-19 }}. MSc. Thesis, The Norwegian University For Science and Technology, Trondheim.</ref>\nThe district is the homeland of the [[Raji people]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Thapa L. B., Dhakal T. M., Chaudhary R., Thapa H. | year = 2014 | title = Medicinal Plants Used by Raji Ethnic Tribe of Nepal in Treatment of Gastrointestinal Disorders | url = | journal = Our Nature | volume = 11 | issue = 2| pages = 177\u2013186 | doi = 10.3126/on.v11i2.9645 }}</ref> Tharu people from Dang settled in the valley since at least the 19th century.<ref name=Krauskopff1995>{{cite journal | author = Krauskopff G | year = 1995 | title = The Anthropology of the Tharus: An Annotated Bibliography | url = | journal = A Journal of Himalayan Studies | volume = 17 | issue = 3&4| pages = 185\u2013213 }}</ref>\nIn recent decades there has been increased migration from surrounding mountain districts as well as other parts of the country. [[Birendranagar]] is the district's capital.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nImagery of ''Surkhet'' ('''S'''):\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.35,81.6219&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x640&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:S%7C28.5791,81.6219&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D28.5791,81.6219&zoom%3D12&size%3D640x640&maptype%3Dsatellite&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\n====Dang and Deukhuri Valleys====\n[[File:NepalDangDistrictmap.png|thumb|Map of the settlements in Dang-Deukhuri District]]\nBoth valleys are located in the [[Dang Deukhuri District]] of the [[Rapti Zone]] in mid-western Nepal.<ref name=Krauskopff1995/>\nThe Dang Valley ({{lang-ne|\u0926\u093e\u0919 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) lies between the Mahabharat Range in the north and the Churia Range in the south.<ref>Sharmai, D. R. (1988). Archaeological Remains of the Dang Valley. Ancient Nepal 88: 8\u201315.</ref> It forms a\nnearly {{convert|1000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} plain within a local drainage basin of less than {{convert|3000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. It is drained by the [[Babai River]], and is one of the largest Inner Terai valleys.<ref name=Mugnier>{{cite journal | author = Mugnier J. L., Leturmy P., Mascle G., Huyghe P., Chalaron E., Vidal G., Delcaillau B. | year = 1999 | title = The Siwaliks of western Nepal: I. Geometry and kinematics | url = | journal = Journal of Asian Earth Sciences | volume = 17 | issue = 5| pages = 629\u2013642 | doi=10.1016/s1367-9120(99)00038-3}}</ref>\n[[Ghorahi]] is the largest city and the administrative, economical and educational center of Dang District.It has a fair weather airport with code DNG. Other towns in the valley include Tulsipur, Tripur and Laxmipur. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nThe Deukhuri Valley ({{lang-ne|\u0926\u0947\u0909\u0916\u0941\u0930\u0940 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) is southeast of the Dang Valley and extends about {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} in WNW-ESE direction with a maximum width of {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Kimura>Kimura, K. (1998). Geomorphic Development of the Deukhuri Dun, Nepal Sub-Himalaya. The science reports of the Tohoku University, 7th series.</ref> It forms a nearly {{convert|600|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} plain within a drainage basin of {{convert|6100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Mugnier/> The valley is drained by the [[West Rapti River]].<ref name=Kimura/> It emerges from its gorge through the Mahabharat Range and flows WNW along the axis of the Siwalik Range between the [[Dundwa Range]] along the India border and the Dang subrange to the north. It flows {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} in this direction until the Dundwas fall away near [[Banke District|Banke]], and the river can resume flowing SE toward the [[Ganges]].{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nThe [[Mahendra Highway]] passes through the Deukhuri Valley.<ref name=Mugnier/> Both valleys are settled by Tharu people,<ref name=Krauskopff1995/> and used as winter pasture by [[Kham Magar]] from the hills.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nImagery of Dang ('''A''') and Deukhuri ('''E'''): \n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.9471,82.4538&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse terrain] [https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.9471,82.4538&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dsatellite&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:A%7C28.0659,82.3096&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:E%7C27.8330,82.5458&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\n===Central Terai===\n\n====Chitwan Valley====\n[[Image:Narayani districts.png|thumb|Narayani zone: the Chitwan district is marked in yellow]]\n\nThe [[Chitwan Valley]] ({{lang-ne|\u091a\u093f\u0924\u0935\u0928 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e}}) encompasses the districts of [[Nawalpur District|Nawalpur]], [[Chitwan District|Chitwan]] and [[Makwanpur District|Makwanpur]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of central Nepal. It is {{convert|150|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and roughly {{convert|30-48|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide.\nThe cities of [[Bharatpur, Nepal|Bharatpur]], [[Ratnanagar]] and [[Hetauda]] are in the valley. It is drained by the [[East Rapti River|Rapti River]] flowing from the Mahabharat Range near Hetauda, then west down the valley to join the [[Narayani River]] west of [[Meghauli]]. The Narayani is also called Gandaki further upstream and Gandak in India.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nImagery of ''Chitwan'' ('''C'''):\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.45,84.44&zoom%3D9&size%3D640x480&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:C%7C27.57,84.49&sensor%3Dfalse terrain]\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D27.59,84.42&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x350&maptype%3Dsatellite&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\nThe [[Chitwan National Park]], Nepal\u2019s first national park established in 1973, was declared a World Heritage site by UNESCO in 1984. It contains the largest and least disturbed natural [[Shorea robusta|Sal]] hill forest and associated communities. Its fauna comprises [[Bengal tiger]], [[Indian leopard]], [[Indian Rhinoceros|great one-horned rhinos]], wild [[Asian elephant]], [[gaur]], golden [[monitor lizard]], [[gharial]] and [[marsh crocodile]].<ref name=nbrb2007/>\n\n===Eastern Terai===\n====Kamala Valley====\n[[Image:Sagarmatha districts.png|thumb|right|Sagarmatha zone: Udayapur district in green]] \nThe Kamala Valley, also called Udayapur Valley ({{lang-ne|'''\u0915\u092e\u0932\u093e''' or '''\u0909\u0926\u092f\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0909\u092a\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0915\u093e'''}}) is in [[Udayapur district]] in southeastern Nepal ([http://ncthakur.itgo.com/districtmaps/udayapur_district.htm Sketch map]). It is about {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and between {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} and {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide. It is drained by the Triyuga river flowing east to join the great [[Koshi River|Koshi]]. This valley lies between the Mahabharat Range to the north and the [[Sivalik Hills]] to the south, with an average elevation of about {{convert|430|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>Darsie, Jr, R. F., Pradhan, S. P., & Vaidya, R. G. (1992). [http://www.mosquitocatalog.org/pdfs/MS24N01P023.Pdf Notes on the mosquitoes of Nepal: II. New species records from 1991 collections] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219183024/http://www.mosquitocatalog.org/pdfs/MS24N01P023.Pdf |date=2008-12-19 }}. Mosquito Systematics 24: 23\u201328.</ref> [[Triyuga]] is the main town.\n\nThe mouth of the valley opens onto a {{convert|175|km|mi|abbr=on}} rectangle of land where the Triyuga meets the Koshi river above the [[Kosi embankment|Koshi Barrage]]. It was designated the [[Koshi Tappu Wildlife Reserve]] in 1976, and is home to the last remaining population of [[wild Asian water buffalo]] in Nepal. The reserve is mostly wetlands, subject to seasonal flooding, but also includes some grasslands and small patches of riverine forest. It is a [[Ramsar Site]].<ref name=nbrb2007>{{Cite book|author=Bhuju, U. R., Shakya, P. R., Basnet, T. B., Shrestha, S. |title=Nepal Biodiversity Resource Book. Protected Areas, Ramsar Sites, and World Heritage Sites |place=Kathmandu |publisher=International Centre for Integrated Mountain Development; Government of Nepal, Ministry of Environment, Science and Technology; United Nations Environment Programme, Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific |year=2007 |url=http://books.icimod.org/demo/uploads/ftp/Nepal%20Biodiversity%20Resource%20Book.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726170342/http://books.icimod.org/demo/uploads/ftp/Nepal%20Biodiversity%20Resource%20Book.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nImagery of Kamala valley:\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D26.8,86.85&zoom%3D10&size%3D640x640&maptype%3Dterrain&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:K%7C26.7824,86.7947&sensor%3Dfalse terrain]\n[https://maps.google.com/maps/api/staticmap?center%3D26.8,86.85&zoom%3D10&size%3D480x480&maptype%3Dsatellite&markers%3Dcolor:blue%7Clabel:K%7C26.7824,86.7947&sensor%3Dfalse satellite]\n\nTraditionally, the Kamala Valley was primarily inhabited by the [[Dhanwar Rai language|Dhanwar]] people (or Danuwar),<ref>Khatry, P. (1995). [http://www.thdl.org/texts/reprints/contributions/CNAS_22_01_04.pdf The Manjani System of the Danuwar State of the Kamala Valley: A Brief Study of an Egalitarian Judiciary]. Contributions to Nepalese Studies 22 (1): 43\u201355.</ref> but there is a fast-growing population of migrants from the Nepali hills and from India.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inner Terai Valleys of Nepal}}\n[[Category:Valleys of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Terai-Duar savanna and grasslands]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Grasslands of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Plains of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Wetlands of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Bheri Zone]]\n[[Category:Janakpur Zone]]\n[[Category:Karnali Zone]]\n[[Category:Rapti Zone]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChitwan Valley:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_Terai_Valleys_of_Nepal"}
{"title_page": "Toto Sudarto Bachtiar", "text_new": "'''Toto Sudarto Bachtiar''' (12 October 1929, [[Cirebon]] \u2013 9 October 2007, [[Bandung]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.antaranews.com/berita/80106/penyair-totot-sudarto-bachtiar-meninggal-dunia|title=Penyair Totot Sudarto Bachtiar Meninggal Dunia - ANTARA News|last=antaranews.com|newspaper=Antara News|language=id-ID|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> \nwas an [[Indonesian language|Indonesian-language]] poet and translator active from the 1950s to the 1970s. He published two volumes of poetry,\n\n* [[Etsa (collection of poems)|''Etsa'']] (1956)\n* [[Suara (collection of poems)|''Suara'']] ('A Voice') (1958)\n\nHis better-known poems include ''Pahlawan Tak Dikenal'' (Unknown Heroes), ''Gadis Peminta-minta'' (The Begging Girl), ''Ibukota Senja'' (Twilight Capital), ''Kemerdekaan'' (Independence), ''Ode I'', ''Ode II'', and ''Tentang Kemerdekaan'' (About Independence).\n\nIn addition to writing poetry, Bachtiar translated [[Jean Paul Sartre]], [[Anton Chekhov]], [[Ernest Hemingway]] and [[Rabindranath Tagore]], among others.\n\nBachtiar's poetry has been described as having \"a haunting lyric grace\",<ref>Burton Raffel, 1967. ''The Development of Modern Indonesian Poetry''. SUNY Press.</ref> but it is notoriously difficult to understand. His verses do not correspond to [[syntax|syntactic units]], he hardly uses any punctuation, and words often do not have a literal meaning. As A. Teeuw described it,\n{{blockquote|What makes this poetry so difficult to understand is the obscurity of its syntactical connections. ... and in addition to this there is his strongly associative, often symbolic use of words. ... Altogether this makes reading these poems very much a matter of groping in the dark. ... [However,] Toto Sudarto Bachtiar is one of the few really original [Indonesian] poets since 1950.|A. Teeuw, 1967. ''Modern Indonesian literature'', p. 211.}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachtiar, Toto Sudarto}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indonesian poets]]\n[[Category:Indonesian translators]]\n[[Category:People from Cirebon]]\n", "text_old": "'''Toto Sudarto Bachtiar''' (12 October 1929, [[Cirebon]] \u2013 9 October 2007, [[Bandung]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.antaranews.com/berita/80106/penyair-totot-sudarto-bachtiar-meninggal-dunia|title=Penyair Totot Sudarto Bachtiar Meninggal Dunia - ANTARA News|last=antaranews.com|newspaper=Antara News|language=id-ID|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> \nwas an [[Indonesian language|Indonesian-language]] poet and translator active from the 1950s to the 1970s. He published two volumes of poetry,\n\n* [[Etsa (collection of poems)|''Etsa'']] (1956)\n* [[Suara (collection of poems)|''Suara'']] ('A Voice') (1958)\n\nHis better-known poems include ''Pahlawan Tak Dikenal'' (Unknown Heroes), ''Gadis Peminta-minta'' (The Begging Girl), ''Ibukota Senja'' (Twilight Capital), ''Kemerdekaan'' (Independence), ''Ode I'', ''Ode II'', and ''Tentang Kemerdekaan'' (About Independence).\n\nIn addition to writing poetry, Bachtiar translated [[Jean Paul Sartre]], [[Anton Chekhov]], [[Ernest Hemingway]] and [[Rabindranath Tagore]], among others. \n\nBachtiar's poetry has been described as having \"a haunting lyric grace\",<ref>Burton Raffel, 1967. ''The Development of Modern Indonesian Poetry''. SUNY Press.</ref> but it is notoriously difficult to understand. His verses do not correspond to [[syntax|syntactic units]], he hardly uses any punctuation, and words often do not have a literal meaning. As A. Teeuw described it,\n{{blockquote|What makes this poetry so difficult to understand is the obscurity of its syntactical connections. ... and in addition to this there is his strongly associative, often symbolic use of words. ... Altogether this makes reading these poems very much a matter of groping in the dark. ... [However,] Toto Sudarto Bachtiar is one of the few really original [Indonesian] poets since 1950.|A. Teeuw, 1967. ''Modern Indonesian literature'', p. 211.}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachtiar, Toto Sudarto}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indonesian poets]]\n[[Category:Indonesian translators]]\n[[Category:People from Cirebon]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toto_Sudarto_Bachtiar"}
{"title_page": "Nigalchula", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Nigalchula\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0928\u093f\u0917\u0932\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e \n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            = Nepal\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Nepal|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Karnali Pradesh]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Salyan District (Nepal)|Salyan District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    -->\n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 1991\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 2443\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.36|82.02|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Nigalchula  ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Salyan District (Nepal)|Salyan District]] in [[Karnali Pradesh]] of western-central [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]], it had a population of 2443 people living in 418 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|work=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=13 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.un.org.np/maps/district-maps/mid-western/Salyan.pdf UN map of the municipalities of Salyan District]\n\n{{Salyan District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Salyan District (Nepal)]]\n\n\n{{Karnali-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  -->\n|name                   = Nigalchula\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0928\u093f\u0917\u0932\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e \n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|ima